{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17480738","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17480738"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:50:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:50:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"101"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"101","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/101"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.16,0.64,0.08,0.12,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"101"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110607"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"101","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/101"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"101"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92852"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"1"},{"type":"tags","id":"32"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"172"},{"type":"tags","id":"1165"},{"type":"tags","id":"1167"},{"type":"tags","id":"2778"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3799"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10717"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11079"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110607","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/110607"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn otherwise healthy 30-year-old woman is reviewed on the ward, 1 day post elective Caesarean Section at 39 weeks gestation. She received a spinal anaesthetic during the operation, and did not have any complications during or immediately after the delivery. She has been complaining of persistent lower back pain for several hours after her surgery. She has not passed urine since her catheter was removed 8 hours ago.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she has 3/5 power in both lower limbs and diminished lower limb reflexes. Her vital signs are normal, and she is otherwise well. She is on regular and PRN analgesia (including opioids), prophylactic subcutaneous enoxaparin and aperients.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Bladder scan","MRI spine","CT spine","No investigations are indicated","X-ray spine"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient\u0027s symptoms and history of spinal anaesthetic for her C-section, suggest a diagnosis of \u003Cstrong\u003Ecauda equina syndrome (CES)\u003C/strong\u003E, a neurosurgical emergency affecting nerve roots L2 and below. Cauda equina syndrome secondary to a spinal haematoma is a rare, but possible, complication of neuraxial anaesthesia, such as spinal block. An \u003Cstrong\u003EMRI spine\u003C/strong\u003E will provide the best definition of the spinal canal and cord, and is the first-line imaging for suspected CES.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile urinary retention is a common symptoms post-CS, and constipation may be caused or worsened by opioid medications, it is important to consider the clinical picture (e.g. lower limb weakness, diminished reflexes). As such, \u0022\u003Cstrong\u003Eno investigations are indicated\u0022 \u003C/strong\u003Eis not correct.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA\u003Cstrong\u003E bladder scan \u003C/strong\u003Ecan be used to assess for urinary retention. While the patient is likely experiencing urinary retention due to CES, a MRI should be prioritised over a bladder scan in order to facilitate diagnosis and management. Whilst a bladder scan could be done, it is not the most appropriate investigation - where the cause of the problem is being sought.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT spine\u003C/strong\u003E (particularly \u003Cem\u003ECT myelogram\u003C/em\u003E) may be considered for patients in whom a MRI scan is contraindicated. However, MRI scans are considered the gold standard in the case of suspected CES.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EX-ray spine\u003C/strong\u003E may show traumatic or destructive bony changes, but would not demonstrate a disc prolapse. It would also not provide visualisation of the spinal cord, as in MRI scans.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Urgent MRI is the investigation of choice in suspected cauda equina syndrome"],"references":["Todd N. Guidelines for cauda equina syndrome. Red flags and white flags. Systematic review and implications for triage. Br J Neurosurg. 2017; 31:336-39.","Long B, Koyfman A, Gottleib M. Evaluation and management of cauda equina syndrome in the emergency department. Am J Emerg Med. 2020; 38:143-48."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92852"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"101"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92852","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92852"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-02T12:12:04+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-02T12:12:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"101"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110607"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"1","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude34","name":"Anaesthesia","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"32","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/32"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurosurgery","synonym